<item>
            <title>[SEC-447] Exploitable XSS in sample apps</title>
                <link>https://jira.spring.io/browse/SEC-447</link>
                <project id="10040" key="SEC">Spring Security</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;There is an exploitable XSS in both acegi-security-sample-tutorial and acegi-security-sample-contacts-filter.&lt;br/&gt;
I assume that a lot of people are using the login page provided as is, just reskinning it. The problem lies in how the username is automatically re-populated after an incorrect login.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;&amp;lt;c:if test=&quot;$&lt;/p&gt;
{not empty param.login_error}&quot;&amp;gt;value=&apos;&amp;lt;%= session.getAttribute(AuthenticationProcessingFilter.ACEGI_SECURITY_LAST_USERNAME_KEY) %&amp;gt;&apos;&amp;lt;/c:if&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
Using the &amp;lt;%= %&amp;gt; tags does not escape html and therefore you could enter something like &amp;lt;script ... /&amp;gt; for a username and probably do some pretty good damage.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
The solution is to use &amp;lt;c:out/&amp;gt; tags with EL instead:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;lt;c:if test=&quot;${not empty param.login_error}
&lt;p&gt;&quot;&amp;gt;value=&apos;&amp;lt;c:out value=&quot;$&lt;/p&gt;
{ACEGI_SECURITY_LAST_USERNAME}
&lt;p&gt;&quot;/&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/c:if&amp;gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment>Irrelevant. JSP.</environment>
